ther of which provided the doctrinal rationale for V. I. Lenin's Bolshevism and Joseph Stalin's communism. This account differs from many others by rejecting a traditional left/right distinction-a distinction that makes it difficult to understand how totalitarian political institutions could arise out of presumably diametrically opposed political ideologies. Marxism, Fascism, and Totalitarianism thus helps to explain the common features of "left-wing" and "right-wing" regimes in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCommunismxHistoryx20th centuryxEurope. 0aCommunismzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aFascismxHistoryx20th centuryxEuropexEurope. 0aFascismzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aTotalitarianismxHistoryx20th century. 0aTotalitarianismxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476999040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804769990423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804769990.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles